element.display: Reporting of pT, pN, and (when applicable) pM categories is based on information available to the pathologist at the time the report is issued. As per the AJCC (Chapter 1, 8th Ed.) it is the managing physician’s responsibility to establish the final pathologic stage based upon all pertinent information, including but potentially not limited to this pathology report.
pT not assigned (cannot be determined based on available pathological information)
pT0: No evidence of primary tumor
pT1: Tumor 2 cm or less in greatest dimension
pT2: Tumor more than 2 cm but less than or equal to 4 cm
pT3: Tumor more than 4 cm or with subserosal invasion or involvement of the mesoappendix

pT4: Tumor perforates the peritoneum or directly invades other adjacent organs or structures (excluding direct mural extension to adjacent subserosa of adjacent bowel), e.g., abdominal wall and skeletal muscle
pN not assigned (no nodes submitted or found)
pN not assigned (cannot be determined based on available pathological information)
pN0: No regional lymph node metastasis
?Not applicable - pM cannot be determined from the submitted specimen(s)
pM1b: Metastasis in at least one extrahepatic site (e.g., lung, ovary, nonregional lymph node, peritoneum, bone)
pM1c: Both hepatic and extrahepatic metastases
